"""
=============================================================================
GRAVITY ANOMALY ANALYSIS PIPELINE
Finite Difference (Explicit)  ↔  Fourier Spectral Methods
=============================================================================

Theory references:
  Farquharson & Mosher (2009) — 3-D modelling of gravity data using finite
      differences. J. Applied Geophysics 68, 417-422.
  Sandwell (2002) — Laplace's Equation in Cartesian Coordinates and
      Satellite Altimetry. UCSD Lecture Notes.

Physical problem (free-space upward continuation)
--------------------------------------------------
Above all mass (z > 0) the disturbing potential Φ satisfies Laplace's eq.:

        ∂²Φ/∂x² + ∂²Φ/∂z² = 0

Boundary conditions:
    Φ(x, 0)  = Δg_surface(x)   [Dirichlet — measured gravity at surface]
    Φ(x, Lz) = 0               [Dirichlet — decay at far field]
    Φ periodic in x

Analytical (Fourier) solution — Sandwell eq. 12:
    Φ̂(k, z) = Φ̂(k, 0) · exp(−2π |k| z)

Finite-difference stencil — Farquharson & Mosher §2:
    Φ[i,j] = w_x·(Φ[i+1,j]+Φ[i-1,j]) + w_z·(Φ[i,j+1]+Φ[i,j-1])
    w_x = 1/[2(1+α²)],  w_z = α²/[2(1+α²)],  α = Δx/Δz

Iteration methods (all EXPLICIT — zero built-in linear solvers):
  • "jacobi"       — standard Jacobi (ω=1), always stable
  • "rb_sor"       — Red-Black SOR, stable for ω∈(0,2), FASTEST  [default]
  • "gauss_seidel" — cell-by-cell Gauss-Seidel + SOR (mirrors the paper)

Stability note: Plain Jacobi with ω>1 (JOR) is UNSTABLE for the Laplacian
because the iteration matrix has eigenvalues near -1, and ω>1 maps them
outside the unit disc.  Red-Black ordering eliminates this issue by
decoupling the two sub-grids, restoring stability for any ω∈(0,2).
=============================================================================
"""

